Artist Zheng Shuai uses an electric rotary tool to carve intricate designs into eggs shells is a sophomore at a college in Shangrao, East China's Jiangxi Province. Screenshot from Pear VideoA young award-winning artist who carves intricate designs into eggshells, include portraits of the powerful and famous, suggested if he never eats another fried egg it will be too soon. Zheng Shuai, 21, said he hasn't had an egg carving since he started carving eggshells almost a decade ago. Now a sophomore at a college in Shangrao, East China's Jiangxi Province, Zhang started carving eggshells by buying more than 100 eggs. Before he begins practicing, he eats all of the yolks and egg whites, which turned him off eggs as food, according to a video posted by Pear Video.Zheng uses an electric rotary tool to carve lifelike portraits of people or Chinese characters onto an eggshell. Many of his works take more than ten hours to complete. "I was touched by the beauty of this craft nine years ago after watching a show on China Central Television. After entering college, I put more time and effort into it," Zheng said."I don't want to eat another fried egg," Zheng said, "but I hope my eggshell carvings are loved by more people.""I hope he can improve his cooking skills so he can try eggs in a variety of ways," said a netizen on Sina Weibo. Pear Video 
